# Report: Why Might a Community Not Be Involved in the Research Process?

## Introduction

Community involvement in research is widely recognized as essential for producing relevant, equitable, and impactful outcomes, especially in public health and social sciences. However, despite the acknowledged benefits of community engagement, many communities remain underrepresented or uninvolved in research processes. This report explores the multifaceted reasons why communities might not be involved in research, drawing on recent and authoritative sources. It examines barriers related to structural, social, cultural, logistical, and power dynamics factors that hinder community participation. The report also discusses challenges inherent in community-based participatory research (CBPR) and community-engaged research (CEnR) models, highlighting why community involvement is often limited or tokenistic.

## Barriers to Community Involvement in Research

### 1. Lack of Awareness and Understanding of Research

A significant barrier to community involvement is the lack of awareness or understanding of what research participation entails. Many communities, particularly ethnic minorities and marginalized groups, have limited knowledge about research opportunities, clinical trials, or the potential benefits of participation. This lack of awareness can stem from insufficient or generic information provided at the outset, which negatively impacts recruitment and retention rates ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)).

Moreover, misconceptions and stereotypes about research—such as beliefs that research is irrelevant or exploitative—can deter participation. For example, ethnic minority groups may hold research stereotypes that feed mistrust and skepticism, further reducing engagement ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)).

### 2. Socioeconomic and Logistical Barriers

Socioeconomic factors play a critical role in limiting community involvement. Costs associated with participation, such as transportation, childcare, and time off from work, pose significant obstacles, especially for low-income populations. Logistical challenges like study location in unfamiliar places, lack of transportation, and absence of childcare support can lead to reluctance or withdrawal from research participation ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)).

Financial constraints affect both participants and researchers. Research involving marginalized communities often requires additional funding and time to build rapport and develop culturally appropriate study materials, which may not always be available ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)).

### 3. Lack of Trust and Power Imbalances

Trust is foundational for community involvement but is often lacking due to historical and ongoing experiences of exploitation, discrimination, and marginalization. Power imbalances between academic researchers and community members can undermine equitable partnerships. Researchers often represent centers of power, privilege, and status, while communities may have experienced structural inequities that foster mistrust ([Ahmed et al., 2020](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7131972/)).

Community-based participatory research (CBPR) aims to address these imbalances by promoting power-sharing and co-governance. However, in practice, researchers frequently retain control over major decisions, limiting true community empowerment ([Ramage et al., 2023](https://researchinvolvement.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40900-025-00706-2)). The failure to adequately address power dynamics can cause communities to disengage or participate in tokenistic ways ([Ahmed et al., 2020](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7131972/)).

### 4. Cultural and Social Context Challenges

Cultural differences and social contexts influence community willingness and ability to participate in research. Language barriers, lack of culturally relevant materials, and differing explanatory models of illness can hinder engagement. For instance, some ethnic minority communities may interpret illnesses differently or perceive research as irrelevant due to cultural beliefs ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)).

Family influence also plays a role, as family members may discourage participation due to concerns about stigma or mistrust ([Khan et al., 2025](https://equityhealthj.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12939-025-02431-4)). Additionally, tensions between community priorities and academic expectations can create challenges in participatory research approaches ([Domecq et al., 2024](https://researchinvolvement.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40900-024-00647-2)).

### 5. Structural and Institutional Barriers

Communities may not be involved due to structural barriers within research institutions and funding mechanisms. For example, lack of research mentorship, limited research opportunities, and absence of a supportive research community can prevent practitioners and community organizations from engaging in research ([Overcoming Barriers to Applied Research, 2016](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7666249/)).

Moreover, the academic research framework often prioritizes individual consent and control, which may conflict with community-based decision-making processes. The demands of academic research, such as the need for control groups or specific study designs, may not align with community needs or preferences, leading to disengagement ([Ross et al., 2011](https://journalofethics.ama-assn.org/article/identifying-challenges-community-based-participatory-research-collaboration/2011-02)).

### 6. Ethical and Psychological Challenges

Research conducted during crises, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, highlights additional ethical and psychological challenges that can limit community involvement. Movement restrictions, social distancing, and psychological stress on both research teams and participants complicate engagement efforts ([Kaawa-Mafigiri et al., 2025](https://bmchealthservres.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12913-025-12691-z)).

Ethical dilemmas arise in balancing research interests with protecting participants and communities, especially in resource-limited settings. These challenges may discourage community participation or result in only superficial engagement ([Kaawa-Mafigiri et al., 2025](https://bmchealthservres.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12913-025-12691-z)).

### 7. Challenges in Sustaining Engagement and Interest

Maintaining community interest and involvement throughout the research process is difficult. Communities may lose interest if they perceive research as irrelevant or if their priorities are not reflected in the study design. Additionally, sustaining contact and participation over time requires resources and commitment that may not be feasible ([Ali et al., 2023](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10094395/)).

### 8. Legitimacy and Representation Concerns

When communities are unstructured or lack formal organization, questions arise about who legitimately represents the community and who has the authority to consent or participate on its behalf. This can complicate engagement efforts and result in exclusion or marginalization of certain groups within the community ([Ross et al., 2011](https://journalofethics.ama-assn.org/article/identifying-challenges-community-based-participatory-research-collaboration/2011-02)).

